In addition, Republican lawyers accounted for only 300 cases of electoral falsifications in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on the appearance of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most of the State Governments since 2009 have passed laws that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon gained new prominence after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in just one year in 2011, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were passed.
The new election laws require the voter to present a photo ID and proof of the existence of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the voter’s right to register on the day of the election, and deprive the citizens of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld in 2008 the constitutionality of the law passed in India.
The Republican authorities have rushed to spread this practice to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills that require voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a medical insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government body.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of citizens over 65, and 20 percent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 don’t have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are believed to be voting for Democratic candidates, in several states are not allowed to use the identity card with a photo issued by their educational institution.
However, these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certificate issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin American voters. . . .
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 to abolish voter registration on the day of the vote in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction has not passed without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 election, the voter registration campaign helped to list about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early-voting voters were African-Americans, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s total number of voters.
The same thing happened with Latin American immigrants as well.
With only 11% of the electorate, they were 24% of the citizens who voted prematurely.
Unlike whites, who make up 76% of voters, only 46% of those who voted prematurely.
Of course, Democrats and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The operation of the most ambiguous laws was suspended with the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the filing of a photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of Democrats condemn the bias of laws that have been passed, seeing them as an obvious direction to influence the results of the 2012 election in key states.
The 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the appearance of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
