Boson Higgs in detail
Last summer’s report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real excitement – and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much.
Moreover, this is the last particle whose existence has been predicted within the Standard Model—our best, or, at least, the “least imperfect” description of nature and the behavior of matter—but which has not previously been able to be discovered by experience.
But physicists aren’t quite sure that it’s the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for the full assurance of some data is not yet available.
Let’s imagine, though, that it’s about the Higgs boson, because the chances of making mistakes seem minimal, and let’s see what that means.
There is a law in this world that says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
To circumvent this rule there is no possibility, even do not try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of this kind: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which posits that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, that they are in the same state, that they are not in the same state, that they are in the same state.
On the basis of this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find well-ordered citizens, called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
In another, there are bosons, a vicious gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can quietly be in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, quite unusual) of Berkeley’s Particle Adventure Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: the mesons that we will not talk about here, and the “parts of the force” through which the main forces of nature are spread by the boson and to whom.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic beings as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it’s thanks to one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “part of the light,” which is the “currier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field at that particular location, about like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "infringement" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of "power transmitters".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, you need to reach very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be rocked by a very large rock.
That’s why you need a huge particle accelerator, like the one that’s being operated at CERN – the Big Adron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never be kept in the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photons, by the way) do not.
So what can all these studies "bring", Mrs. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to check the accuracy of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to find a difference between the results of observations and SM forecasts.
In addition, some of them are passionately longing for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest inconsistency can open the door to "new physics" and close some of the Model's holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant flaws, without offering any explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But so far, no such differences have been found in CERN.
Consequences
The benefit of these studies for the average person’s daily life is more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it is not.
In the early 60’s, pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs couldn’t even guess what revolution their work would bring.
They envisioned their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the already deceased physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where in 1960 a laser was invented, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previously impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was "considered as soon as possible."
Imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the instrumentation accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, though not at all its original purpose, now serves as an “eye” for all the world’s digital cameras and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows, in fact, that everything can be.
