Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin’s price, reaching a maximum of $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in this system in its report on virtual currency, published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competiting with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to ordinary currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote video games that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations are always controlled and processed by any central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously bookholders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers, and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between the two users actually takes place between the two e-mail addresses, similar to e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
A key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical task sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It is a phase of file hashing, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers will “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros in the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of fraud, the user very quickly (in less than ten minutes) would like to pay twice the same amount of money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly divided into halves, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one stamil, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from the reserves.
“The defect used does not apply to the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Nuaz, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizman Institute in Israel, analyzed the account book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant Sales" was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, a Coinabul employee who is engaged in the conversion of bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nuez, another author of the grant on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to check transactions, which thus comes out cheaper.
The owner has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It’s enough just to report an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, says Pierre Nuaz, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is confirmed, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
In its report, the ECB intends, by the way, to review the various risks that are considered to be raised today in the event of the success of this system.
