The Hard Births of the Constitution of Egypt
This is a risky move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever, on the issue of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, it has decided to play a va-bank.
He announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text for the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It has been two years since Egypt relied on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only strengthened the country's division.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic edge", continuing to "break the word" and "resist the right".
In the camp, his followers are convinced that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by speeding up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brothers to give up the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, the article after the article.
For the president, this is also a way to restore social and democratic legitimacy, while dissatisfaction is raging across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for expedited voting goes to the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Whether you vote for my text, or I leave myself with extraordinary powers,” which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to express their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
In order for the required quorum to be reached, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the article was voted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, mocked the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... time for prayer, as some members of the committee considered that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were wrong.
The text, on which the vote was still held yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained an identical article of the 1971 Constitution, arguing that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace the “principles” with the “rules”, which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Physicianism," answer the liberals, who see this only as a pear.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to checking compliance with Shariah laws.
According to Egypt’s expert Sophie Pomye, this is alarming, because “people who are called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.”
We can observe the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals, in addition, are outraged by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
“There is no specific religious intervention at the moment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema, and people with university education, some have studied in the French system," said Alexis Bloe, who prepares a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that “there may be ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious lexicon.
This applies in particular to "fixes" [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And in the future, there may be a question of how competent civil judges are to make decisions about this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is subject to criticism, as it gives wide powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers claim that they have decreased significantly compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the authority of the army.
In accordance with the military wishes, the consideration of the defense budget will take place not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will it be prohibited to prosecute civilians in military courts, despite the requests of human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered detrimental to freedom.
The responsibility for blasphemy has been maintained, and insult has now been banned, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles speak more about the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Moraef, from Human Rights Watch.
