Poland and Space.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ECA in 1994 and during the following years took an active part in a number of projects of the Agency.
But the journey to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I will recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory the idea of his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltra and Andre Luis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Spacecraft".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great proponent of astronomy and cosmonauts.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned cosmonautist, and his contribution was appreciated including that one of the craters on the opposite side of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway crane was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as did the details of the project.
It is not even clear that a rocket had to be used to disengage or to brake the truck.
Information about this tree is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket fires.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
From the preserved materials it can be seen that the studies have reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric launcher rocket, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in a specialized press, and the following year came out the work "Air torpedo rocket and aerial bomb" by author Lelyva-Kzhivoblotsky.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Prior to the war, all projects of military use of missile equipment were undertaken by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymchasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended due to the start of the war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautych).
For the first time, the society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problems", which publishes four volume articles on astronomy.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would engage in cosmonautism.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the POA has become its real member.
And the following year, the first president of the International Astronautics Federation Kazimez Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the vice president of the International Astronautics Federation.
He remained in this position until his own death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of exceeding a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were carried out on the Bled Desert.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high winds.
But in 1962, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types (labelled as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1V - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight distance of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to lift a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Cosmic Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
