In November 1979, a crowd of Islamic student protesters seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pehlevi, who fled after the U.S. revolution, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, the positive outcome of the situation was not expected – it could not afford to throw a chessboard because it could fundamentally undermine the trust of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the liberation of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
Detained diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations with the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, which ended in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult peripheries, they ended their journey to the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, while helping an extravagant cover legend, according to which they went through Canadian passports as members of the shooting team, searching for a place in the country to shoot a science fiction epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by “evacuation” expert Tony Mendes, demanded Hollywood’s cooperation.
In order for the legend to be reliable, the specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, arranged a press conference, the fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-kinoup", the story of a successful snooze, an affair - an example can be a number of films about Oushen's friends.
The moods in the film are constantly changing – on the one hand, the documentary-designed scenes from Tehran (in the titles are shown marked historical photos of events and the way the same situations were shown in the film – there are no major differences in this).
On the other hand, the relief of Hollywood fragments intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then more scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in costumes discuss the situation behind the negotiating tables, on the stairs of the institutions, by phone ...
Ben Affleck had a great start to his career.
From the ridiculed actor he became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third full-length film, after the dark detective "Hello, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film, which is not filmed in the native city of the director - Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated the director’s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in "Argo", where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, when real events are reconstructed - the opening scenes of the embassy fall impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere suddenly history changes.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his colleagues in the fictional scenes (the subordinate headquarters at the Tehran Bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not imply many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
It works quite successfully with this few, sometimes something comes up - there all this does not come out so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the looming crisis at the airport of Tehran, and a drive on the runway).
The disadvantage of "Argo" is the dispersion associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood co-stars are really very amusing, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of dramatism, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the setting and retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to catch.
However, this is enough to remind us of one, still in the known sense of living history, as well as to testify to the exaggerated perceptions of all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence services.
