Sabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stefan Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, in doing so, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the request of the Palestinians to obtain observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
- Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, while not speaking too critically about Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO has made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it is moving from a policy, which, so to speak, was governed by the United States, to German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that for the time being they are only finding their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy pursued by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is the willingness to take a position in their national interests, independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are vastly different from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be cautious so as not to offend the public and the elite in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't give it too much importance, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States there is a predominant understanding of the German position.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic as in the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even acquire a certain amount of respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different views on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, spoke clearly for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that the significant differences in opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, the Germans would have been a little easier if there were a single, uncontroversial European policy, but now it is not.
