Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's statements about the poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions were cruel.
The U.S. Army is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that serial Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint for ill-treatment, which, according to him, he had to go to war.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mide, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Feyn said that the records of Manning's weekly visits by representatives of the prison administration during his nine-month detention in Kwantiko, Utah.
A cross-examination as part of the consideration of Manning’s defence application on the grounds that his detention was violent and in itself sufficient punishment was carried out the day after Manning stated that he was in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that the source of the information was Manning.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Feyn, together with Manning, reviewed reports that were filled out after Manning's visits by representatives of the administration during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the prison administration’s appeal to him as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reports under consideration do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of its content, Feyn claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concern about these problems and that the representatives of the administration who attended him discussed these problems with him and stated that they would deal with them, but did not record it in writing.
“They recorded ‘no problems’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the issue in the conversation,” Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain of an irregular treatment with him in January 2011 during a commission meeting that examined the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing in a matter of months.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to achieve a “traumatic prevention” regime and soften the conditions of detention.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that the restricted detention regime - at a level lower than the supervisory regime in order to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them canceling the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view," Manning said.
On Thursday, Manning testified of his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that thoughts of suicide appeared in him in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to a strong heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not told how your participation is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has reached the Camp Arifjan base, the size of my prison," Manning said Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cell.”
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small camera - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the day prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he constantly had light in his eyes, penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning into a bed at night, then, according to him, he was awakened and forced to turn his back.
Manning's lawyer filed an official objection to the illegal treatment of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge asked Manning for a statement he made while giving evidence on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning said he had not been able to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to the judge’s questions on Friday, Manning said that he understood from the guard’s order that he should drop a blanket that could be covered, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to drop it.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a rubber band of cowards or sleds to traumatize himself, but he didn’t.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he has had to live through during the incarceration, and will significantly shorten the time of the incarceration if Manning is found guilty by the military court, which is due to begin consideration of his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty for less serious crimes, and other charges to challenge him as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the content of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
Among the charges brought against Manning include assisting the enemy, illegal promotion of the publication of data on the Internet, transmission of information relating to national defense, and theft of state property or documents.
If he is convicted on all points of the indictment, he may face a life sentence.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the country’s residents of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexicans of American origin split between the two cultures.
During my recent trip to Mexico, I walked down the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone, and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), and the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican my whole life.
It’s just a conditional name, like what my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York consider themselves Italians.
Later I stopped at the complex construction of "American of Mexican descent".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of the speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That’s why I got my American passport and became the order for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the questions used to meet the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto spoke about the rise of the Mexican economy, which will allow Mexicans now, with the same success, to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the U.S. and Canada and create some North American trading bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto has promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals have been made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
The majority of Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the duress of guns, forced its leaders to abandon half their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not for minutes, and they see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only for any U.S. government official to speak out at least with the word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elites of Mexican society immediately complain that the Americans are reaching for the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montesuma are overrun with militancy.
At the same time, Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
You want to talk about abuse?
That's enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those who do not.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone—father or grandfather—had no chance of making a living in Mexico and was forced to leave.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - striped, under-trained, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we have studied in good schools and have done good work, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider its own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as non-real Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our relations with Mexico aren’t strong enough.
Only our existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not now be behind the silk curtain, finding a living life in the United States, but having lost spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the U.S. as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican descent - Mexicans clearly understand their national identity, and this American.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes that she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
By getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations were not yet sufficiently confused, some Mexican leaders and representatives of the intelligence community want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican descent to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent her interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
Nothing's gonna work out.
Too many attempts in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the rise of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, Amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still offended by how recently the Mexicans have treated them.
Yeah, yeah.
I guess we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could become a fragile foundation for a future world.
Is it possible for a long-term peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed is pushing for the conclusion about the futility of such hopes.
It sounds like the usual, meaningless arguments about who started the first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of them civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time during the conflict, Israelis have been released from exile from the territory.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians have been hopelessly tied up in their eternal conflict, there have been changes in the Middle East.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have surrounded in the rebel storm a lot of established realities, and the Palestinians with the Israelis have failed to stay away from the storm that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope to get out of this deadly deadlock.
War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give reasons for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, say they have forced Israel to step down despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million residents have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic parts of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River – another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working on them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, new influential and wealthy friends emerge in Hamas.
Turkey, a regenerating regional leader who was once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas; its example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas’s pro-democracy supporters declare the creation of an Islamic crescent around Israel – from Lebanon to the north, which is dominated by the Hezbollah militant group, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are now overthrowing the power of Bashar Assad, Daesh, and Daesh.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Brotherhood-Muslim movement under President Mohammed Morsi was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay special attention to the support of Hamas.
The Muslim brothers, on the other hand, are an organization, much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In the future, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice will not be able to silence even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system "Iron Dome" justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the launched Hamas missiles.
Israelis can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States remained true to its unchanging position; many European countries also blamed the beginning of the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, particularly with the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, about 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the territory of the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of terrorists-killers, in part because of the wall that enters the territory of the West Bank from the Jordan River, and is not a significant part of the country.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the elections scheduled for 22 January - has united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Liberman, is very convenient.
What’s the point of slaughtering the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they put all the power in their hands on the West Bank, won’t they start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as their counterparts in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the supporters of the "hard" line will win; however, their calculations may be rejected by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and other countries, are not experiencing the warmest feelings towards Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense portion of Israel’s budget is larger than that of all its Arab neighbors, taken together.
Deploying a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help the governments of Arab countries strengthen their own economy.
