To miss the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at the airport, because our plane found mechanical malfunctions and was replaced by another plane that we were expecting.
Thus, I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Getting to the airport while waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help here.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in children’s development are expressing themselves in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to distract from interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the advantages of boredom pass by us.
Maybe we should try to get bored?
Yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
Previously, I, like many, thought that boredom was an invention relatively recent times when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
“In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin inscriptions of boredom dating back to the first century.
There is still an open question about how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, adjunct professor at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
Studying the research materials on this topic and asking the question of the target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boring is when people “want, but can’t do, what would bring them satisfaction.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a boring person doesn’t do something he wants to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the experiencing boredom, he says, is "a violation of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is running out slowly."
According to the description, boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, people who are bored see the causes of problems in the surrounding world and circumstances, and people who are depressed see problems in themselves.
Sometimes it seems to us that we are bored when in fact we just find it difficult to focus on something.
In his study, “The Unbearable Mind: Determination of Attention Fatigue,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previously conducted experiment whose journal participants listened to a recording of the voice.
Some of the participants also heard loud noises outside of the TV program included in the neighboring room, others heard the same low-noise sounds, so they could hardly be heard, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without the sound of strangers.
Those participants who heard a low-noise TV noted that they were bored, more often than others – they were hard to focus on, but they didn’t know the reasons for it and attributed it to boredom.
When we’re trying to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fensk, adjunct professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.”
It is believed that when people start to climb on a chair or draw karakuli on a sheet of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study showed that children who are not prohibited from snoring and snoring are learning better and remembering more information than children who are required to sit down,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point we all experience boredom: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching a non-interesting film.
However, different people show different degrees of tendency to boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual features, the researchers developed a special "scan to boredom scale".
To determine a score on such a scale, questions and affirmations are used, such as “A lot of what I have to do, uniformly and monotonously” or “I’m too much interested, so there’s no time for anything.”
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially if there are a variety of external irritants.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
He received the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he does not have any data on what kind of data would be on boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "at adolescence there is a peak of tendency to boredom", mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s go back to my original question: is boredom useful?
Sometimes it is not, because in extreme manifestations it can, as research shows, push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or abuse certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have been thinking about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
“So our brain tells us to do something else; that’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
However, this same brain does not always know what is best to do.
If you get bored and you focus that energy on playing the guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll make yourself better.
However, if you are going to watch TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child misses and you give him an iPad, he will stop missing, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way manage his time and employment,” says Professor Fenske.
“And such skills of self-regulation are involved in a wide variety of situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to do something on his own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think the boredom needs to be exaggerated.
However, to think of it as something bad is also not worth it.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of actions and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with this.
“We see this in a way that we need to experience boredom more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, tireless desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people try to get away from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we’re used to the constant overstimulation of the sense organs, and when there’s silence, we’re lost and we don’t know what to do.”
