Hector "Hettin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Busy basketball traveler Hector "Hettin" Reyes has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector "Hettin" Reyes.
And before the brain hemorrhage led him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a small-class player, player of the Higher Basketball League, authorized and head of the BSN with Cuban President Fawboy.
“I’ve played many basketball roles throughout my life, including several at the same time as when I was president of BSN, general manager of the National Team and president of the federation in the 1990s,” Reyes recalls during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamon, where he lives.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes is not exaggerating by making this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorable things collected for his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest emotions he keeps those who remember his path through the Cowboys, from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Kovboev championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There have been many years of joy, including five championships, held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said good-bye to one in 1981, the year of Jerome Minsey's BSN debut.
From that moment on, Kuko Ortiz, who was a great administrator, continued to lead,” Reyes said.
I remember Jean Bartov, who went here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7."
"Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Minsi, one of the best players who was at Puerto Rico.
Bartov then recommended the sniper Raymond Gauss, who received citizenship and became one of our best bombers.
I remember what I said, if Minsey had brought the championship to Bayamon, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the championship of the Cowboys with Gauss, but already at a distance, because by 1988 it was already meant to be the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and Minsi’s achievements in the national team.
I remember the first time we won the U.S. Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we got fourth place and it was supposed to be bronze, if not the Canadian judge who made us replay the final game, Reyes said.
That team from the 1990 World Cup is the best team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best as well as the one that she won at Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite was that since the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and broke the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won our bronze at the World Cup.
Not only did Minsi, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico Lopez and Piculina (Ortis) play on that team again, but also young (Havier) Tonito Colon and James Carter, brothers Leon (Fran<0xC3><0xA7>o and Edgar) and Mario "Kyhote" Morales, who did not participate in the 90-year-old Mario "Kyoke" Morales.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of personal composition, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With cast members such as Canito Neves, Pablo Alisea and young Rolando Hurruitner in exchange for players temporarily removed for disorder in the Pan American Mar del Plata championship, we won gold against all forecasts.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortis.
His performances at international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Piculin did.
And that’s without taking into account his career in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's a very difficult question.
We had a very good young man, including Julio Toro, Flora Melendes, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
From a young age, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you think is your main achievement in the Federation?
Participated in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 1990s BSN had up to 17 teams per season.
What's left for you to do?
There were things that I wanted to implement, for example, the regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, the boys from Ponce played only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in national playoffs.
Now the guys are traveling and playing too much, and that’s redundant.
At least, I see the fruits of mandatory certification and coursework for managers, officials and judges.
This gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Icabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hemman has died.
Larry Hegman, born September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his lead role as John Ross Young, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied a maniac without principles.
Larry Hegman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Young in the television series Dallas, became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hegman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night from complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the Dallas production studio.
"Larry has returned to his favorite hometown of Dallas, playing a landmark role again, which he liked the most," his family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving party.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was next to Hegman when he died in Dallas hospital, her representative, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, kind and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived a full life,” Gray said in a statement.
Hegman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was found to have a malignant tumor in the liver, and he underwent a transplant.
Long before "Dallas", Hegman gained fame on television due to his role as a regular in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive gypsy girl played by Barbara Eden, and begins to live with her under one roof.
He was also the main character of two comedies that rarely appeared on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included roles well-received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the admirablely disgusting J.R. that brought Hegman to the top of the fame.
The CBS drama series about the Jung Clan and other characters in its surroundings aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan “Who shot at J.R.?”, designed to create noise around an episode full of emotions in which Hegman’s character is almost unkillable, spawned international discussions and the millions of dollars they risked in bookmaker’s accounts.
It also helped to bring the series to a record audience at that time.
When the answer was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second most viewed entertainment program in history, after the 1983 MASH final, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s niece, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. interfered with her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hegman played Yuing as an insatiable corrupter with a charismatic smile: an dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be put on treatment.
"I know what should be on J.R.'s grave slab," Hegman said in 1988.
It should be said, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Young."
This is the only deal he has lost.
Victoria Principal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled on Friday Hegman as someone "big, both on and off screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of every one of us who has been fortunate enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were shown a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes of the second season has already been completed and the sixth was in production, the channel reported.
Warner or TNT have not yet made statements about what will happen to the series after Hegman's departure.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who excelled in such classics as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hegman.
He tried his luck on the New York theater scene in the early 1950s, and then served in the British Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
While there, he met the young Swedish artist May Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities live.
In 2001, he named his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
“I didn’t include anything that I thought would be able to hurt someone or affect them in any way,” he told the Prensa Asociada.
After transplanting the liver, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in the hospital to help patients experiencing fear.
“I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go into surgery, and then,” he said in 1996.
I’m trying to offer some comfort, like, “Don’t be afraid, it’ll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but you’ll be fine.”
He also actively opposed smoking and participated in several campaigns.
